<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="168" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1394,2601,3095,3489]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1395,1643,3370,3403]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 66-88 mm, tail 30-45 mm, ear 10-14 mm, hindfoot 11-13 mm; weight 9-13 g. Tail of the Short-tailed Shrew 
<taxonomicName box="[2139,2235,3415,3444]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Tenrec" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Tenrec</taxonomicName>
is less than 60% of headbody length. Hindfootis relatively short. Dorsal pelage is moderately short, coarse, and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[766,1359,300,727]" pageId="7" pageNumber="168">brown, with buffy brown speckling; venter is pale grayish brown. Tail scale hairs are moderately short, and scales are visible.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="168" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[766,1359,300,727]" pageId="7" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[768,879,426,451]" pageId="7" pageNumber="168">Habitat.</emphasis>
Humid forests, dry forests, and transitional dry to humid forests at elevations of 20-1150 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
